abstract: A city councilman is pushing to make public the code behind city decisions on everything from school assignments to trash collection.
snippet: A city councilman is pushing to make public the code behind city decisions on everything from school assignments to trash collection.
lead_paragraph: Let us say that James Vacca is not necessarily the first person you’d think would begin a deeply necessary revolution to peel away some of the secrecy around technology that shapes government decisions. In the 1980s, Mr. Vacca admitted, he told an aide that it would be a waste of money to replace office typewriters with word processors.

abstract: Schools in the city’s Renewal program received extra resources, but an analysis of their state test scores shows uneven results despite the big investment.
snippet: Schools in the city’s Renewal program received extra resources, but an analysis of their state test scores shows uneven results despite the big investment.
lead_paragraph: When it comes to New York’s schools, Mayor Bill de Blasio has placed his biggest bet on the Renewal program, which has pumped extra money and other resources into a group of the city’s most troubled schools, at a cost of $582 million.

abstract: A Times survey of New York City museums reveals that the lack of diversity starts at the top — with the board.
snippet: A Times survey of New York City museums reveals that the lack of diversity starts at the top — with the board.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio gave New York’s museums and arts groups an ultimatum last month: Take steps to make your staff and leadership more diverse, or risk losing part of your city funding.

headline_print_headline: In New York, Hub of Diversity,  Museums’ Boards Skew White

abstract: Is it worth it for the M.T.A. to brand subway stops? The Irish Spring Street station?
snippet: Is it worth it for the M.T.A. to brand subway stops? The Irish Spring Street station?
lead_paragraph: Among the cash-raising ideas for New York City’s woebegone subways is Gov. Andrew Cuomo’s suggestion to let businesses slap their names on stations — for a price, of course. The governor said a few weeks ago that a $600,000 contribution might be the ticket to buy into an “adopt a station” program. The money would go to cleaning and repairs. In return, the sponsor would have its name on display so the train-riding public could marvel at its civic virtue.

abstract: In some of his most direct comments to date, Mayor Bill de Blasio said a proposal to charge drivers to enter congested areas of the city was not fair or equitable.
snippet: In some of his most direct comments to date, Mayor Bill de Blasio said a proposal to charge drivers to enter congested areas of the city was not fair or equitable.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio said that he “does not believe” in a proposal to charge drivers to enter New York City’s highest-traffic areas and use the proceeds to fund its ailing transportation network, an approach known as congestion pricing, which has lately gotten a boost from Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo.

abstract: Calling himself “Bannon the Barbarian,” the president’s former strategy adviser says he’s ready to “crush” his foes inside and outside the White House.

lead_paragraph: Stephen K. Bannon left the White House with a frightful howl indeed.

headline_main: Behind the Bluster of Steve Bannon’s #War Cry

abstract: Support has been hard to come by, but it’s an efficient way to raise money for mass transit, cut down on traffic and limit pollution.
snippet: Support has been hard to come by, but it’s an efficient way to raise money for mass transit, cut down on traffic and limit pollution.
lead_paragraph: Some New York politicians have argued that the State Legislature will never approve a system of tolls and taxi fees, known as congestion pricing, which could help reduce traffic on the streets of Manhattan and pay for much-needed transit improvements. Getting lawmakers to back this idea will be difficult, as former Mayor Michael Bloomberg’s failed effort a decade ago shows, but it ought not to be impossible.

headline_main: Gov. Cuomo’s Wise Move on Congestion Pricing

abstract: New York pays more than 800 teachers without permanent jobs. Now it plans to put them into school vacancies, whether principals want them or not.
snippet: New York pays more than 800 teachers without permanent jobs. Now it plans to put them into school vacancies, whether principals want them or not.
lead_paragraph: For a dozen years, hundreds of New York City teachers have been paid despite not having permanent jobs, sidelined in most cases because of disciplinary problems or bad teaching records or because they had worked in poorly performing schools that were closed or where enrollment declined.

abstract: Mayor de Blasio ran on a platform of ending income inequality, and had no natural kinship to Wall Street. Four years later, little has changed.
snippet: Mayor de Blasio ran on a platform of ending income inequality, and had no natural kinship to Wall Street. Four years later, little has changed.
lead_paragraph: In 2014, one of New York City’s largest private employers, JPMorgan Chase, sought to make a deal with the newly minted administration of Mayor Bill de Blasio. The company wanted to move thousands of workers to a pair of new office towers in the Hudson Yards development, but it demanded a host of incentives from the city to make it happen.
